Job Exec Waiting

CSPlanExecutorWaitForResult

This lock indicates that a SQL executor waits for its job workers executing a column store statement (thread method: PlanExecutor calc). So it is basically an "idle" lock and itself not critical. If the lock is visible for a long time, you have to check why the execution of the SQL statement by the job worker(s) takes so long.

Mutex Wait ZipResultInput_SectionLock This lock can appear in the context of parallel sorting. Only threads of the same statement execution can block itself, so it is usually a local effect. If this lock appears frequently, you should analyze and optimize the related SQL statements (SAP Note 2000002).

ConditionalVar Wait
ConditionalVariable Wait

ParallelIndexHash_cond

This lock wait is typically linked to thread method 'HashDict worker' and it impacts parallel job workers processing the same database request. See SAP Note 2114710 (Thread Method = 'HashDict worker') for more details.

Massive waits for this lock are typically a consequence of an expensive database request (SAP Note 2000002), involving intermediate results (dicts) in contexts like calculation scenarios or joins.

With SAP HANA Rev. <= 1.00.121 it can happen that after an out-of-memory situation threads permanently remain in a state waiting for ParallelIndexHash_cond. This bug is fixed with SAP HANA Rev. 1.00.122.00.
SharedLock Enter
ExclusiveLock Enter		 JoinEvaluator_JEPlanData_Lock

This lock situation happens when multiple threads of the same join engine job need to access the same plan data objects. This is a rather normal situation so that it is not necessarily an issue that this lock belongs to the most frequent ones in a system. The lock waits are always local to a single request / single connection. If the locks result in performance issues, you should check if the underlying SQL statement is already processed optimally or if it can be tuned (SAP Note 2000002).

These thread methods are linked to the creation of special intermediate results of database requests, so called hash dicts. Mapper threads ("worker") and reducer threads ("merger", "merging") collaborate. If mappers (small result set) or reducer (large result set) take longer, synchronization is done with the ParallelIndexHash_cond lock (SAP Note 1999998).

A high amount of threads in these methods typically indicates an expensive, parallelized SQL statement. You can check according to SAP Note 2000002 if tuning is possible.

ConditionalVariable Wait

ParallelIndexHash_cond

This lock wait is typically linked to thread method 'HashDict worker' and it impacts parallel job workers processing the same database request. See SAP Note 2114710 (Thread Method = 'HashDict worker') for more details.

Massive waits for this lock are typically a consequence of an expensive database request (SAP Note 2000002), involving intermediate results (dicts) in contexts like calculation scenarios or joins.

ConditionalVar Wait
ConditionalVariable Wait

merger_queue_cond

This lock can show up when the result of an OLAP engine request, parallelized across several job workers, is merged. See SAP Note 1999997 ("Which general optimizations exist for reducing the SQL statement memory requirements?") in order to make sure that SQL statements are executed as efficient as possible. Contention is always local to the JobWorker threads processing an individual parallelized operation.
Mutex Wait ParallelIndexHash_queueSection

These locks are used in context of thread method "HashDict worker" and contention usually happens when high cardinality data is processed. Only threads related to the same parallel operation are blocked, there is no global contention. You can reduce contention by optimizing the underlying SQL request (SAP Note 2000002) and by making sure that reasonably small concurrency settings like default_statement_concurrency_limit are in place (SAP Note 2222250).

These locks are visible when a thread has delegated the work to one or more parallel JobWorker threads and waits for the results. It can be considered as idle wait.
Mutex Wait CSPlanExecutorLock

Job worker threads of a parallelized execution have to wait for other threads of the same connection. You can consider these waits as idle waits. In order to improve the performance and reduce the wait time, you have to check what the other threads of the same connection are doing and how their activity can be optimized (e.g. by eliminating lock scenarios, resource bottlenecks or expensive SQL statements).

The related call stack module is e.g. Executor::X2Handle::set or Executor::SwitchGuard::acquire.

Mutex Wait ParallelIndexHash_queueSection

These locks are used in context of thread method "HashDict worker" and contention usually happens when high cardinality data is processed. Only threads related to the same parallel operation are blocked, there is no global contention. You can reduce contention by optimizing the underlying SQL request (SAP Note 2000002) and by making sure that reasonably small concurrency settings like default_statement_concurrency_limit are in place (SAP Note 2222250).
Mutex Wait

JE_SynchronizedNTuple_Lock

This lock synchronizes a parallelized creation of tuples during join operations. It only locks threads belonging to the same parallelized statement execution. If you repeatedly suffer from these lock waits, you may suffer from a bad SQL statement or an inefficiently processed join. See SAP Note 2000002 and check if you can optimize the underlying SQL statements.

ConditionalVar Wait
ConditionalVariable Wait

ParallelIndexHash_cond

This lock wait is typically linked to thread method 'HashDict worker' and it impacts parallel job workers processing the same database request. See SAP Note 2114710 (Thread Method = 'HashDict worker') for more details.

Massive waits for this lock are typically a consequence of an expensive database request (SAP Note 2000002), involving intermediate results (dicts) in contexts like calculation scenarios or joins.

With SAP HANA Rev. <= 1.00.121 it can happen that after an out-of-memory situation threads permanently remain in a state waiting for ParallelIndexHash_cond. This bug is fixed with SAP HANA Rev. 1.00.122.00.

These thread methods are linked to the creation of special intermediate results of database requests, so called hash dicts. JE_SynchronizedNTuple_Lock

This lock synchronizes a parallelized creation of tuples during join operations. It only locks threads belonging to the same parallelized statement execution. If you repeatedly suffer from these lock waits, you may suffer from a bad SQL statement or an inefficiently processed join. Thread State Lock Name Information from Note 1999998 (Updated on 2021/08/14)
Running ? Request execution, typically CPU consumption

Job Exec Waiting

CSPlanExecutorWaitForResult

This lock indicates that a SQL executor waits for its job workers executing a column store statement (thread method: PlanExecutor calc). So it is basically an "idle" lock and itself not critical. If the lock is visible for a long time, you have to check why the execution of the SQL statement by the job worker(s) takes so long.

The use of cyclic joins can be controlled via CYCLIC_JOIN / NO_CYCLIC_JOIN hints (SAP Note 2142945).
